TY  - JOUR
T1  - Tax Clienteles and Asset Pricing
AU  - DYBVIG, PHILIP H.
AU  - ROSS, STEPHEN A.
Y1  - 1986/07/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1986.tb04540.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 751
EP  - 762
VL  - 41
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1986.tb04540.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Taxation of asset returns can create various clientele effects. If every agent is marginal on all assets, no clientele effects arise. If some (but not every) agent is marginal on all assets, there arises a clientele effect in quantities but none in prices. If no agent is marginal on all assets, there arise clientele effects in both quantities and prices. In the first two cases, standard asset pricing and martingale results extend to analogous aftertax results. In the third case, linear asset pricing works only on subsets of assets, and the standard martingale results become after-tax supermartingale results.
